  "doc_id": "5200",
  "text": "Our study has significant strengths and some potential limitations. Because of the high resolution possible with HRpQCT (voxel size, 82 mm), our data are perhaps at the limit of feasibility in terms of assessing bone microstructure in vivo in humans using a technology that has been validated for both trabecular and cortical parameters against the current gold standard, mCT (which can only be used in excised bones). [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Nonetheless, we recognize that even with this high resolution, the parameters we assessed using HRpQCT are likely estimates of the true measures. In addition, our cross-sectional findings need to be confirmed by longitudinal studies, but it is important to note that these estimates seem to change in a predictable manner through puberty and reflect differences that have been observed in adults using bone biopsies. For example, our demonstration of a higher BV/TV and Tb.Th at the wrist toward the end of puberty in boys compared with girls is exactly what has been observed for differences in trabecular structure by histomorphometry in men versus women using iliac crest bone biopsies. [CITATION_3] Thus, given limitations on radiation exposure, HRpQCT is perhaps the best validated tool to assess bone microstructure in humans, especially children.",
